riences, events and memories across regions and nations including Scotland, Wales, Italy, Norway and the Netherlands, paying careful attention to often-overlooked groups including drug users, sex workers, nurses, mothers and people in prison. Offering new perspectives on the development and implementation of policy, the nature of activism and expertise and which (or whose) histories are remembered, it is essential reading not only for historians of health but also for all those working in HIV/AIDS studies.Electronic versions of chapters 3, 4, 6, 7 and 8 are available under a creative commons licence: www.manchesterhive.com/view/9781526151223/9781526151223.xml  afunded by Wellcome Trust  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAIDS (Disease)xPolitical aspects. 0aAIDS (Disease)zEurope, WesternxHistory. 0aHIV infectionszEurope, WesternxHistory. 7aMEDICAL / History.2bisacsh  aActivism.  aArchives.  aDrugs.  aHarm reduction.  aHealth policy.  aLGBT.  aMuseums.  aNursing.  aOral history.  aQueer theory.1 aAppasamy, Nathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerridge, Virginia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeGrazia, Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDickinson, Tommy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDziuban, Agata, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElizabeth, Hannah J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElizabeth, Hannah J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJanuschke, Eugen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlöppel, Ulrike, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeeworthy, Daryl, econtributor.4c